<br>
Well Cerien, if due process is too expensive it can always be trashed right?  Hey, if death saves money Somthor- why don't we just shoot criminals in situ at the site of their crime?  Thieves, jaywalkers, panhandlers- why even bother with all that cumbersome police paperwork- just KILL EM ALL!!!!~£$@~<br>
<br>
Whatever the arguments for or against state-sponsored murder of citizens, if you're going to bring cost into it then as well to ask why we even have judicial process.  No need to dig through the archives either, in the last 3 years alone there have been over 450 miscarriages of justice wiped off the books in Britain, 80 of which are capital crimes in many US states.  Pretty shocking when you consider the UK has the third lowest rate of miscarriage per head of population in the developed world.  80 less people, hundreds in the US if you consider the differing crime rates- how many innocents die before the &quot;savings&quot; are no longer worth the price?<br>
<br>
I say one, others may try and juggle the numbers, good luck to them.  The Marquis de Sade understood the nature of execution 200 years ago, remarking: <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>to kill a man in a paroxysm of passion is understandable, but to have him killed by someone else after calm and serious meditation and on the pretext of duty honourably discharged is incomprehensible <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Say what you will about the French, but their writers/thinkers certainly know how to crystalise an issue~<br>
 <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
