Death penalty trials are very costly relative to county budgets. Capital cases burden county budgets with large unexpected costs, according to a report released by the National Bureau of Economic Research, &quot;The Budgetary Repercussions of Capital Convictions,&quot; by Katherine Baicker. Counties manage these high costs by decreasing funding for highways and police and by increasing taxes. The report estimates that between 1982-1997 the extra cost of capital trials was $1.6 billion. (NBER Working Paper No. w8382, Issued in July 2001) Read the abstract. <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Total cost of death penalty 38% greater than total cost of life without parole sentences.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> A study by Indiana's Criminal Law Study Commission found this to be true, assuming that 20% of death sentences are overturned and resentenced to life. (Indiana Criminal Law Study Commission, January 10, 2002) <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>North Carolina spends $2.16 million more per execution than on a non-death penalty murder case.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The most comprehensive death penalty study in the country found that the death penalty costs North Carolina $2.16 million more per execution than the a non-death penalty murder case with a sentence of life imprisonment (Duke University, May 1993). On a national basis, these figures translate to an extra cost of over $1 billion spent since 1976 on the death penalty.  The study,&quot;The Costs of Processing Murder Cases in North Carolina&quot; is available on line at www-pps.aas.duke.edu/people/faculty/cook/comnc.pdf. <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Florida spends $51 million extra per year on death penalty.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Florida would save $51 million each year by punishing all first-degree murderers with life in prison without parole, according to estimates by the Palm Beach Post. Based on the 44 executions Florida has carried out since 1976, that amounts to an approximate cost of $24 million for each execution.  This finding takes into account the relatively few inmates who are actually executed, as well as the time and effort expended on capital defendants who are tried but convicted of a lesser murder charge, and those whose death sentences are overturned on appeal. (Palm Beach Post, January 4, 2000) <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>California spends $90 million annually beyond ordinary costs of justice system.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> $78 million of that total is incurred at the trial level (Sacramento Bee, March 18, 198<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> . In January 2003, despite a budge deficit, California Governor Gray Davis proposed building a new $220 million state of the art death row. (New York Times, January 14, 2003) <br>
Florida spent average of $3.2 million per execution from 1973 to 1988. During that time period, Florida spent an estimated <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>$57 million on the death penalty to achieve 18 executions.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> I think this statistic is key.  What did you site, something around $1.5 million for three appeals?  Obviously, the cost exceeds that greatly.  (Miami Herald, July 10, 198<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Each death penalty case costs Texas average of $2.3 million. That is about three times the cost of imprisoning someone in a single cell at the highest security level for 40 years.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> (Dallas Morning News, March 8, 1992) <br>
<br>
Most maximum security prisons in this country cost between $20,000 to $40,000 per year to hold an inmate.  Even at 40 years in the some of most costly institutions in the country, the total is only $1.6 million dollars.  And I think most of you would agree, that given the choice between living the last 40 years of your life seeing the light of day once per two weeks or just having the lights turned out, you'd choose the latter.  Simultaneously, it preserves the sanctity of true and fair justice in this land of eroding democracy. <br>
<br>
Oh yeah, and here's some information on state sponsors murder of innocents: <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://sun.soci.niu.edu/~critcrim/wrong/wrong.html">sun.soci.niu.edu/~critcri...wrong.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bollixbraker>BollixBraker</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 52<br> <font color=#333333>(11/20/03 7:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=428.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Some basic tenets of a good criminal justice system:<br>
1. innocent until proven guilty<br>
2. right to a fair trial<br>
3. guilt must be proven beyond a reasonable doubt.<br>
A basic tenet of somthor's criminal justice system:<br>
1. bullets are cheaper than courts.<br>
<br>
Ok, that was delibarately over exaggerating your position somthor for the purposes of argument.<br>
<br>
Your argument does have some pragmatic benefits, it would be cheaper to execute than to keep people in prison for long periods.  One follow somthors argument and disagree wtih cephus and point out that death penalty is so expensive because we have far too many appeals.  However, from a moral perspective the argument that &quot;it is cheaper to kill than to keep alive in prison&quot; has serious flaws.  By the same token, it is cheaper to let old people die than to provide them with health benefits, or those with disabilties will drain our resources, or that the poor don't deserve social security as they are net 'takers' from the system.  I don't think you can place a fiscal value like this on human life.  It detracts too much from the moral values on sanctity of human life. <p>Bollix Braker <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Warlord <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Officer <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Celestial Empire <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--> <br>
