<br>
So you would support torture, indefinate sensory deprivation, mutilation, amputation and pretty much any other form of degradation because you think crime negates all rights?<br>
<br>
With that sort of attitude you'll forever be focused on reacting to crime rather than preventing it.  And that after all is the ultimate goal here- our justice system shouldn't be, as Jeremy Bentham once put it:  &quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Akin to a master watching his dog with a rolled up parchment, waiting for it to err that he may strike it upon the nose</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;<br>
<br>
We should prevent crime- and that's very difficult to do if criminals are deprived of the basic right to life.  A merciless consequence like that, quite apart from the fact you might be wrong...sends completely the opposite signal to criminals.  <br>
<br>
The death penalty does not deter, look at any study you like, compare places without the death penalty to places with it- you'll in fact find that in the majority of cases, states in America with the death penalty actually saw an *increase* in crime since they introduced it.<br>
<br>
It is as I say- extremely difficult to discourage first time offenders, to reach out to young people thinking about crime- extremely difficult for them to look upon us as a way out- if the ultimate consequence is death.  The impression created is that criminals have no way out, no way back- and if falsely convicted, the gravest possible injustice is done without the possibility of restitution.  That makes potential future criminals wary of listening to crime prevention programmes, wary of the police, wary in fact of anything to do with the government.  These are people that have as yet committed no crime, and only need a gentle shove in the right direction- the presence of a death sentence can often make that difficult.<br>
<br>
This is why crime is far more effectively prevented through persuasion rather than coercion- for the same reason segregation didn't work and for the same reason colonisation ultimately failed:  the state should be limited in the extent of rights it can revoke.  If not, injustice is the result Sighkox- as you typed your post btw, did it even cross your mind how many hundreds of *innocent* people have and may have been executed?  Think about that happening to you or someone you know, and perhaps you'll think again.<br>
<br>
 <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
65 Archon<br>
