<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Read what I wrote carefully- I never said &quot;thought innocent&quot;, I said innocent.  As in, they did not commit the crime, yet were executed for it.  Recent history in certain US states is littered with examples of this- no one's rights are served by the execution of an innocent individual.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I ask you to consider a situation where a family member of yours is raped and murdered, and the criminal who did so spends 10... maybe 15 years in a state prison watching cable TV, enjoying internet access and earning his college equivalency degree on your dime<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Now we're getting down to brass tacks, and a good thing too.  Is the only goal of justice to punish, or is there a rehabilitative aim?  In other words, is our prison system in place simply to confine, or to release a productive citizen that has paid their debt to society.  <br>
<br>
I certainly don't think cable TV and internet access should be a part of any prison system (it certainly isn't here in the UK, forget TV full-stop, never mind cable or internet).  They're not their to be entertained, they're there to pay a debt and hopefully to be reformed into something other than a criminal.  I fail to see why you object to education however- not college equivalency certainly- but a basic course of education, if requested, could well help people to see the errors of their ways and turn them into citizens rather than disenfranchised and hardened criminals.  <br>
<br>
Justice should not be only about punishment- punishment alone does nothing for the victims except sate a brutal desire for revenge- something any of us should be ashamed of.  There is no point in justice officially disapproving of vigilantism and the concept of revenge, whilst actively encouraging such behaviour through a legitimate process- eg, cheering crowds waving placards at an execution.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>A true criminal forfeits their rights by their actions<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ok, do I understand then that you support the torture of prisoners, dismemberment, public humiliation, brainwashing, medical experimentation a la Holocaust, and pretty much any similar dehumanizing treatment?  Or do you concede that criminals are human beings and do have rights.  If you deny the notion of even basic humane treatment rights, then you support torture- if not, then you concede they do have some rights.  Can't have it both ways friend.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Do not paint these people out to be violated saints.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I never said they were, don't put words in my mouth.  Yes they are criminals and they have offended, perhaps seriously- but what do we or the victims' families gain simply by punishing them?  Nothing, absolutely nothing.  No amount of physically harming the criminal will bring back a murdered friend, or undo the offence.  A debt to society must be paid, absolutely agree with that- but execution?  The chance that the person executed is innocent places a horrible risk in the path of justice, precisely the sort of risk we should actively avoid.<br>
<br>
  I'm just pointing out that no matter their crimes, they're still human beings and are entitled to basic rights.  I personally believe that we shouldn't simply lock criminals away only for the sake of punishment- that's a horrible waste of a person, a waste of money and an admission of defeat.  I think that where prison can reform people, it should be allowed to, and we could all benefit from it.  <br>
<br>
After all, if someone is rehabilitated, will not offend again, and can make a positive and hardworking contribution to society- why should we not welcome that?  Must it be the case that your life in prison is 100% negative?  If so, then all prison is likely to achieve is to turn first time offenders into hardened criminals and excaerbate the problem.  Unless of course you propose all jail sentences are extended to life.  <br>
<br>
Here's an analogy- there was a time when people genuinely thought all drug use could be deterred or prevented.  There was no concept of rehabilitation, users were simply locked away from the public, even executed in the early years, no attempt was made to help or rehabilitate them.  Western society has since accepted that treating and rehabilitating drug addicts goes hand in hand with deterring further use.  <br>
<br>
Moreover, it helps prevent future crime for the sake of addiction, and brings us productive citizens again.  There are many victims of drug addiction besides the user- although it's not a crime to cause people close to you emotional distress, that is certainly arguably as undesirable as being the victim of a crime.  The rights of the victims were balanced here because of the understanding that rehabilitation benefitted society, whereas revenge has nothing on the positive balancesheet.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It benefits society to be just and fair, and for our system to engage in due process to apply justice accurately<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well I'm glad we agree on something.  Where we differ fundamentally it seems, are what constitute acceptable risk when condemning an individual to die.  I think you'll accept that it is impossible for any justice system to apply itself accurately to all cases, particularly where juries and high profile crimes are concerned.  As such, in applying the death penalty, you seem willing to accept the possibility that people no guiltier than the victims of a crime will be executed unjustly.  <br>
<br>
In accepting that innocent people have and will continue to be executed, I cannot help but feel you are abandoning the moral high ground.  It's one thing to talk about accurate justice, quite another to blindly accept the execution of innocent people to sate the revenge of a victim and the bloodlust of the public.  <br>
<br>
