<br>
A quote like this is saturated with appeals to emotion and assumptions. Are you actually conversing with me, or looking for acceptance and help from others in discussing your convictions? There's no need for that. <br>
<br>
Furthermore, it's not about a moral high ground to preach from. It's about making the right choice for the most. I'd also hope that you'd give me more credit then one who &quot;blindly accepts the execution of innocent people to sate the revenge of a victim and the bloodlust of the public.&quot; You do yourself injustice by making yourself out to be a fanatic rather then a reasonable person.<br>
<br>
So far, the best argument I've seen you present concerning the death penalty has to do with it's validity in a justice system that makes mistakes. Can capital punishment, a solution that is final, be reconciled with a system that has several layers of appeals?<br>
<br>
I believe it can. Part of having a justice system that can act with authority is the assumption that the rulings it makes are correct and fair. If we undermine ourselves by assuming we imprison innocent people, there's a whole realm of problems.<br>
<br>
I'm just going to ignore the paragraph about torture and mutilation (because it's utterly ridiculous), but I will address the point. Yes, they forfeit their right to be treated like equal members of our society. They lose their freedom, felons lose their right to vote, etc etc. That does not give us a free ticket to violate, mutilate and humiliate them. We very well could because we are in the right, but we do not because we are not a malevolent society. We recognize that it would do more harm then good.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Now we're getting down to brass tacks, and a good thing too. Is the only goal of justice to punish, or is there a rehabilitative aim? In other words, is our prison system in place simply to confine, or to release a productive citizen that has paid their debt to society. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This struck me as the most meaningful portion of your post, and I agree that this should be the heart of the matter.<br>
<br>
Ideally we'd hope to prevent as many crimes as possible. Failing that, we'd hope to be able to rehabilitate offenders so that their first offense was their last. After thousands of years of locking people up, you think we'd know how to do just that, right? Nah... the nature of criminal activity is still very vague for us. It's a very heated topic in sociology. <br>
<br>
Assuming we knew exactly what to do for each person that entered our prisons, would we have the resources to do what was necessary? It will be a long time before that's possible in the U.S., where we're still warming up to the idea of social welfare. The idea of having to pay taxes to feed, educate and entertain the guy who robbed/killed your family still isn't quite 'okay' with us yet, on a large level. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Must it be the case that your life in prison is 100% negative?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Hmm... yes.<br>
<br>
Why should we afford criminals in prison things we can't give to our productive, useful citizens? Also, why should the prison experience be a positive one?<br>
