-Junk <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=taranna>Taranna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>HiElf Snob</span><br>  Posts: 984<br> <font color=#333333>(11/20/03 6:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=428.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Long post- apologies, but there is rather a lot to cover.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>A quote like this is saturated with appeals to emotion and assumptions<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
No it's not- I'm not appealing to either- just giving you my opinion.  *I feel* you're abandoning the moral high ground, that is *my* perception.  Read carefully, I need no help from others to justify my convictions...the fact that I'm posting on an American forum where a large majority support the death penalty should surely suggest to you that I require nothing of the kind.<br>
<br>
I'll ignore the characterisation of me as a fanatic- I'm nothing of the kind.  I'm posting on this board in the full realisation that a majority of people will oppose the right to life of some criminals.  I've assumed that the majority of posters here believe in a moral code of jurisprudence as simplistic as &quot;an eye for an eye&quot;.  I've also assumed (correctly in this case I'm sure), that none of the posters here have read Bentham, HLA Hart, or Ronald Dworkin.  Given these assumptions, I'm trying to argue to an audience that is unable to grasp the basics of an inclusive social structure- so I beg your indulgence for how it seems to come across- it isn't easy to argue within such restrictions.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If we undermine ourselves by assuming we imprison innocent people, there's a whole realm of problems.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Another totally misleading statement- I never said we *assume* that we imprison innocent people, I merely said that it happens.  That is a fact, not an assumption- actually it's a fact that reccurs with alarming regularity.  <br>
<br>
I don't think we should assume those convicted are innocent- but at the same time I believe it's our duty to acknowledge that it does happen, and not that rarely.  A layered appeals process is meaningless for example, if a jury is the main convicting authority- for reasons I've explained in earlier posts.  If an appeals judge has no access to the reasoning behind a conviction (juries are not required to provide this)- then how can the judge overturn a decision based on rationale + the facts?  The case has to be judged exclusively based on what is presented by counsel, rather than what the convicting authority made of said material.  <br>
<br>
So, if you think it through- it isn't an appeal at all- the first appeal is simply an appeals process hearing the same evidence the jury did in a slightly different timeframe.  An appeal is supposed to be a process of judicial review, not judicial groundhog day.  Fact is, with a jury conviction heard by politically appointed judges- one can be even less certain about the integrity of an appeals process.<br>
<br>
I'm not saying it doesn't work- but what I am saying is that if we're still executing innocent people- then it doesn't work <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>well enough</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to cope with a fundamentally irrevocable sentence.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'm just going to ignore the paragraph about torture and mutilation (because it's utterly ridiculous), <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't see that it is ridiculous at all.  You don't have to look any further than Camp Delta to see that the &quot;spread of freedom across the world&quot; doesn't apply if you're randomly labelled an &quot;unlawful combatant/enemy combatant&quot;.  A status incidentally that has no place in international law or US law.  Either they are POWs and are repatriated under terms of the Geneva Convention's Article V- or they are charged and tried in a court of law with recourse to appeal.  <br>
<br>
There isn't any way you can tell me that solitary confinement for 23 hours, sensory deprivation, white noise, blinding luminar lamps, and the evidence of 3 men beaten to death in military custody (one at Bagram Airbase, two at bases within the US)- there's no way you can tell me those don't amount to torture- or at least criminal behaviour.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>That does not give us a free ticket to violate, mutilate and humiliate them. We very well could because we are in the right, but we do not because we are not a malevolent society<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
This is beginning to look less and less ridiculous of an argument isn't it.  I think it can be convincingly argued that a society that murders its citizens as a part of &quot;due process of law&quot;, locks up hundreds of people without trial, abridges rights of counsel, client privelage, tortures prisoners selectively, and beats some to death without transparent consequence- I think such a society could quite easily be described as malevolent.  <br>
<br>
A society with a greater number of prisoners per head of population, one that imprisons more people than it provides healthcare for.  I think it's very much an open question whether the fabric of that particular society is or isn't malevolent.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>After thousands of years of locking people up, you think we'd know how to do just that, right? Nah... the nature of criminal activity is still very vague for us<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You know, I recall an ethical debate that was studied by us in my first year as a medical student.  It argued that even though we'd been attempting cures for certain STDs and various forms of lung cancer and heart disease for thousands of years, we should stop.  Because after all, STDs are only really spread through &quot;immoral&quot; behaviour, lung cancer is 95% caused by cigarette smoking and heart disease is 97% caused by lifestyle choices.  Plus, the psychology of why people knowingly inflict long-term harm on themselves by smoking, eating fatty foods or drinking their livers into a white pulpy mess- that psychology and reasoning is still vague.  Doesn't mean we should give up.<br>
<br>
Now why don't we just add- 95% of executions that we know of, were executions of guilty individuals.  That last 5% doesn't matter, casualties of the system.  Thank goodness we didn't come to that conclusion at the debate, on the right to treatment or right to life.  Again, it simply comes down to how much you value (or don't value) human life.  If you can accept that 5% at least will be innocent murder victims of the judicial process then you might as well apply the same moral logic across the spectrum of society.  <br>
<br>
I don't accept that you can argue for treating self-inflicted illness with compassion while refusing to treat criminal offenders with that same compassion.  The reasoning is simple- 3%, or 5%, probably even more than 5% don't fit the bill, and I don't accept that their fate must be inevitable.  Because without the death penalty, we may keep alive criminals whose blood the public bay for- but we'll also save hundreds of lives.  Everything from my professional calling to my conscience leads me to that choice.  If it doesn't suit others, then I feel sorry for them.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It will be a long time before that's possible in the U.S., where we're still warming up to the idea of social welfare<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Well, spending a little less than 20% of your total budget on defence would help.  None of that figure contributes to Homeland security incidentally- all of it goes to the Pentagon.  Spending perhaps not as little as 5%...but 9-10%?  With the size of the US economy that's more than enough.  And it'd free enough money to cover every citizen with healthcare and near-free tertiary education.  Raise taxes on the rich by a single percentage point and...well, you get the idea.  Making the initial sacrifice of social welfare isn't easy- but the results pay off.  <br>
<br>
Preventing crime is made a lot easier by a prison system that is willing to work with offenders rather than against them.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Why should we afford criminals in prison things we can't give to our productive, useful citizens? Also, why should the prison experience be a positive one?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Dealing with your second point- why should it be entirely negative?  That doesn't solve anything- in fact, you'll likely create a far bigger problem when prisoners are released.  They are often disenfranchised and recidivism is the inevitable consequence of hardening criminals with purely punitive measures.  Working *with* offenders is far more likely to yield results, not just in prison but outside- people will listen far more easily if you show them there's a way out.  With no way out of the prison system, there is little incentive to avoid the risk of crime.<br>
<br>
As far as your first point goes, if you nationalized tertiary education funding and provided universal health cover, that issue wouldn't ever arise.  It doesn't in Britain, nor does it arise in Europe- because everyone- prince or pauper, chemist or criminal have universal access to health care.  Tertiary education is cut off to criminals here...but they can still better themselves.<br>
<br>
Am I saying prison should be a positive experience?  No, it shouldn't- but neither should it be 100% negative.  The emphasis should be on confinement, 0 entertainment but with the opportunity for prisoners to better themselves.  Assuming all citizens have equal access to that- it doesn't create the conundrum you pose.  Plus, you are improving society as a whole.  Here's an example- one of my friend's former colleagues served 5 years in prison for GBH.  He became interested in the sciences while inside, the prison consular officer introduced him to some reading material, and 6 years later he ended up saving the life of the man he committed GBH against 11 years previously.  <br>
<br>
OK, 99% of rehabilitated and bettered criminals will never directly benefit the people they harmed- but they will benefit society as a whole, that is not arguable.  Incidentally, I talked to my friend's work colleage a year ago- and he's a changed person, the experience of prison changed him- not through fear, but through understanding of wrongdoing.  One prisoner given that chance is a far greater achievement than a hundred executions.  The greater the depravity of a criminal, in all but the most extreme cases- the greater the potential for rehabilitation.  That's what I believe profoundly, and it is not a view that requires assent or consensus- it's simply a paradigm of jurisprudence I hold to be right.<br>
<br>
 <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
65 Archon<br>
Ascending Dawn, RZ</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=taranna>Taranna</A> at: 11/20/03 6:24 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=murlen01>Murlen01</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 60<br> <font color=#333333>(11/20/03 7:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=428.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1>      Well, I think we could make a novel out of this post.  I don't think Somther ever intended this poll to end up like it did.  I think he really wanted to find out what people thought of the death penalty, thus the poll.  <br>
<br>
     I don't think that this poll is going to change the thought of anyone regarding the death penalty.  There is no substitute for experience, and lets hope that no one ever has to go through the experience of having a crime relevent to the death penalty be committed against them or a loved one.<br>
<br>
     Personally I don't know how I would react if something like that ever happened to someone I love.  But I know I would not be happy to see someone get out of prison 15 years later, when I will never be able to see that loved one for the remainder of my life.  God I know see how people can sit here and write books on this subject.<br>
<br>
     I think I would have to agree with Vorge on this, but with one change.  Shouldn't it be a Marine sniper and not an Army sniper? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=smawty>smawty</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 26<br> <font color=#333333>(11/21/03 2:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=428.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Criticism of judicial decisions fall into two categories: A judge's interpretation of law and their interpretation of fact. When you say liberals don't trust judges to sentence someone to death- that is an interpretation of the facts. It's not a point of law (Is there or isn't there a death penalty)- but a point of fact (facts of the case, fingerprints on the gun, DNA/semen samples). The second half of your comparison is dealing with an interpretation of law (is there or isn't there a woman's right to choose for example). <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That is a good point but Judges don't always simply interpret the facts or the law.  Recently the Massachusetts Supreme Court <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>commanded</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the legislature to enact a law allowing gay marriage within 6 months.  This is hardly interpreting the law, in fact it is the judicial system creating new laws.  A job that is supposed to be reserved for the legislature.  Obviously there was no outcry from liberal anti death penalty advocates when these judges let their ideology influence their decision.<br>
<br>
In 2002 anti death penalty lawyers fought hard to take power away from the judges in determining if someone should be put to death.  They succeeded and the Supreme Court ruled that judges could only decide whether or not to put someone to death if the jury had concluded that the crime warranted it.<br>
<br>
Therefore, supporting to limit a judges power in capital crime cases but not minding when a judge oversteps their authority and imposes their ideology on society is being a hyppocrite. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub83.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=taranna>Taranna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>HiElf Snob</span><br>  Posts: 985<br> <font color=#333333>(11/21/03 6:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=428.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>That is a good point but Judges don't always simply interpret the facts or the law. Recently the Massachusetts Supreme Court commanded the legislature to enact a law allowing gay marriage within 6 months.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
From the news reports I've read and from what my dad's told me (he's a judge)- the decision has allowed the Massachusetts legislature 180 days to react to the ruling.  It's important to remember that the job of ensuring a lack of conflict in legislation(one law contradicting or contraindicating another)- is up to judges.  As such, judges do make law- that is the essence of what common law means!<br>
<br>
If judges had no role in making law, then Brown vs. Board of Education wouldn't have forced the end of segregation- state legislatures could have ignored the ruling.  In any common law system where the rule of precedent applies (US included)- judges have the power to make law.  <br>
<br>
Now in a civil law system like France, Germany, Italy- or a Roman-Dutch system like Spain, there is not the rule of precedent- each new case is considered on its merits.  Many people think this is how *all* court systems operate, but they are wrong.  Precedent and the power to streamline output from the legislature is enshrined within an independent judiciary.  <br>
<br>
However, there is one extremely valid and relevant complaint you could make if you happened to oppose same-sex marriage.  That objection is that the judgement makes reference to only a single point of law- one in the state's constitution.  For a test case with no ruling of state precedent to directly alter the meaning of what my dad tells me, is the oldest state constitution in America- that is not exceeding your brief, but it's sure as bloody hell pushing the envelope a bit fast.  A test case or two, a chance for the state legislature to be apprised of a decision like this- the opinion writing judge was in a hurry, according to my dad.<br>
<br>
But then, should we be suprised smawty?  Judges are politically appointed- it's not only &quot;liberal&quot; judges that have a stake- &quot;conservative&quot; judges selected the current president.  Given that two of the judges hearing the case were appointed by his father (both voted for him)- one could argue a gross conflict of political, personal and judicial interests.  Just as whatever political affiliations liberal judges possess have driven them to some of their decisions.<br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong- I support the Massachusetts ruling- I just think it was hastily done, with little time for other arms of government to have a say.  I also supported the striking down of those ridiculous anti-sodomy laws.  However, I didn't support the upholding of affirmative action in education, I find that a disgrace.  But see- those are political opinions.  If judges were selected not by politicians or campaign lobbies- but by their peers and by the bar councils + an independent constitutional figure, these problems would be considerably less.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>They succeeded and the Supreme Court ruled that judges could only decide whether or not to put someone to death if the jury had concluded that the crime warranted it<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Read that carefully- the jury has the power to save a criminal's life, not the judge.  If you read criminology studies, you'll find that juries are far less restrained about such things than judges.  Probably because their understanding of jurisprudence ranks somewhere with my understanding of Mongolian onion-curling.  <br>
<br>
Judges are far more likely to consider the facts of the case rather than how horrible the crim is.  I think if you're going to have something as murderously unfair as a death penalty- it *SHOULD* be in the hands of a panel of 3 judges, NO jury.  That would make the appeal process more transparent and the decision would have to mean something.<br>
<br>
Last point on all of this smawty- if you read through Massachusett's law books, particularly the law of union &amp; marriage- you'll find that gay couples already possess nearly all of the rights of heterosexual couples.  In fact, gay unmarried couples in some cases have more rights than heterosexual unmarried couples.  This is plainly unfair- so to streamline contradictions in the legislation- you legalize gay marriage, and then provide heterosexual unmarried couples with the same rights as unmarried gays had previously.  <br>
<br>
That is the sensible thing to do- if all the trappings of marriage are allowed, but a few key rights (inheritance, family tax, relations binding in law) are absent, surely it makes sense to enfranchise those rights and be done with it.  Otherwise the legislation is just comical, and smacks of state interference to prevent legitimate rights simply because of sexual orientation.<br>
<br>
 <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
65 Archon<br>
